'''Tafu-ke Ōji''' is one of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|fr|Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=99 ōji Shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} on the [[Kumano Kodō]].
== Tafu-ke Ōji == '''Tafu-ke Ōji''' (多富気王子), also romanized as Tabu-ke Ōji, is a historical shrine site located in [[:en:Nachikatsuura|Nachikatsuura]], [[:en:Higashimuro District, Wakayama|Higashimuro District, Wakayama]], [[:en:Wakayama Prefecture|Wakayama Prefecture]], Japan. It is considered the final shrine in the sequence of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} (Ninety-nine Ōji Shrines) associated with the [[:en:Kumano Kodō|Kumano Kodō]], a network of ancient pilgrimage routes. The site is located near the entrance of the {{ill|Daimonzaka|ja|大門坂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daimonzaka|qq=}}, just above the {{ill|Meoto Sugi|ja|夫婦杉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meoto Sugi|qq=}} (Sacred Couple Cedars).
== Historical Background == Unlike many other Ōji shrines, Tafu-ke Ōji is not mentioned in prominent medieval pilgrimage records such as the ''{{ill|Chūyūki|ja|中右記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūyūki|qq=}}'', ''Kumano Dō no Aima Guki'' (熊野道之間愚記) included in the ''{{ill|Meigetsuki|ja|明月記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meigetsuki|qq=}}'', or the ''Shūmeimon-in Sankei-ki'' (修明門院参詣記). Its existence is confirmed primarily through Edo-period geographical texts and travel records.<ref name="kadokawa">Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Editorial Committee (1985), p. 665.</ref>
The ''Kinan Gōdōki'' (紀南郷導記) from the Genroku era describes it as a small shrine (shōshi) related to the nearby Wakaichi Ōji Shrine in the Ninose area of Ichinono Village. In the ''Kumano Junrō-ki'' (熊野巡覧記) from 1794, the site is referred to as ''Chigo-no-Miya'' (児宮, literally "Child Shrine").
== Origins and Significance == The origins of Tafu-ke Ōji remain unclear. There are several theories regarding its name and function: * It may derive from the term ''tamuke'' (手向け), meaning "offering" or "dedication."<ref name="heibon">Heibonsha (1997), p. 624.</ref> * Some suggest it was named after a local priest associated with Nachi Shrine.<ref name="kadokawa">Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten Editorial Committee (1985), p. 665.</ref> * Another theory posits that it served as a purification site (haraisho) for pilgrims visiting Nachi Shrine.
The ''Kii Zoku Fudoki'' (紀伊続風土記) notes that it was dedicated to a [[:en:Dōsojin|Dōsojin]], a type of roadside deity protecting travelers. Although the shrine once had buildings during the Edo period, these were relocated in 1877 (Meiji 10) to the precincts of [[:en:Kumano Nachi Taisha|Kumano Nachi Taisha]], where it was known as ''Chigo-no-Miya'' (児宮). Only a stone monument and a {{ill|Kōshin-zuka|ja|庚申塚|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōshin-zuka|qq=}} (Kōshin Mound) now mark the original site.<ref>Nishi (1987), p. 172.</ref>
== Cultural Designation == Tafu-ke Ōji is designated as a {{ill|Prefectural Historic Site|ja|和歌山県指定史跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prefectural Historic Site|qq=}} by Wakayama Prefecture (designated on April 1, 1958).<ref name="Kinen">{{Cite web|title=Prefectural Cultural Properties: Historic Sites|url=https://www.pref.wakayama.lg.jp/prefg/500700/mokuroku/kenkinenbutsu.html|publisher=Wakayama Prefecture Board of Education|accessdate=2023-10-17}}</ref>
